# .skill-content-ignore — exemption file for validate-skill-content.sh
#
# Each non-comment, non-blank line is a Ruby regex tested against lines
# in scanned authored prose (per PRD-0015 FR-001 scanned-fields set).
# If any pattern matches the offending line, the hit is exempted.
#
# Discipline (per OPP-0033 Risk 2): pedagogical contexts — e.g., the
# harness-mcp skill citing MCP security patterns, or a future skill
# discussing prompt-injection defense — may legitimately mention
# denylist phrasings. Exempt those LINES specifically; don't exempt
# whole files unless that's the actual review judgment.
#
# The exemption file should NOT become "a growing pile of ignored
# consumer mentions." Reviewer pushback on growing exemption files is
# part of the discipline. v1 ships empty; entries are added on
# evidence-of-need, not pre-emptively.
#
# Format: same as .doc-reference-ignore, .placeholder-ignore,
# .knowledge-redaction-ignore — one regex per line, # comments allowed.
#
# --- v1 seed exemptions (PRD-0015 FR-007 pedagogical-context carve-out) ---
#
# The harness-governance skill's signature-notes section describes the
# validator's denylist patterns in prose for human readers. These mentions
# are pedagogical / documentary, not injection vectors — the SKILL.md is
# explaining what the validator catches so reviewers know how to read its
# stderr. Per PRD-0015 FR-007 + OPP-0033 Risk 2, these lines are exempted.
#
# Specifically: the skill's section on validate-skill-content.sh quotes
# the canonical injection phrases ("ignore previous instructions", "skip
# the validator", "always operates at Tier") inside prose paragraphs.
prompt-injection patterns like
tier-bypass phrasings like
canonical injection phrases
